Title: Diagnosis of test `testGenerateURLFragment`
Details: The test `testGenerateURLFragment` checks whether HTML entities such as `"` are correctly escaped to their corresponding character by the `StandardToolTipTagFragmentGenerator.generateToolTipFragment` method. However, the test failure indicates that this is not the case. Following the execution path, we find that `StandardToolTipTagFragmentGenerator.generateToolTipFragment` is not escaping any HTML code; instead, it is using its input `toolTipText` as is. Consequently, un-escaped strings are being returned, which leads to the error demonstrated by the test.

After providing this diagnosis, you will be prompted to suggest which methods would be the best locations to be fixed. The answers should be in the form of `ClassName.MethodName(ArgType1, ArgType2, ...)` without commentary (one per line), as your answer will be automatically processed before finally being presented to the user.

The test `['com.google.javascript.jscomp.TypeCheckTest.testBackwardsTypedefUse8()']` failed.
The test looks like:

```java
2667 :   public void testBackwardsTypedefUse8() throws Exception {
2668 :     // Tehnically, this isn't quite right, because the JS runtime
2669 :     // will coerce null -> the global object. But we'll punt on that for now.
2670 :     testTypes( // error occurred here
2671 :         "/** @param {!Array} x */ function g(x) {}" +
2672 :         "/** @this {goog.MyTypedef} */ function f() { g(this); }" +
2673 :         "var goog = {};" +
2674 :         "/** @typedef {(Array|null|undefined)} */ goog.MyTypedef;");
2675 :   }
```

The passing test with the highest token similarity to the failing test looks like:

 ```1694 :   public void testAbstractMethodHandling6() throws Exception {
1695 :     testTypes(
1696 :         "var goog = {};" +
1697 :         "/** @type {Function} */ goog.abstractFn = function() {};" +
1698 :         "/** @param {number} x */ goog.f = abstractFn;" +
1699 :         "goog.f('x');",
1700 :         "actual parameter 1 of goog.f does not match formal parameter\n" +
1701 :         "found   : string\n" +
1702 :         "required: number");
1703 :   }
```

Title: Diagnosis of test `TypeCheckTest.testBackwardsTypedefUse8`

The failing test expects the parameter types to match the formal parameter types specified in the annotations, but there are mismatches, leading to errors.

The failing test `TypeCheckTest.testBackwardsTypedefUse8` attempts to test the use of typedefs in JavaScript, but due to incorrect type annotations or usage, it results in type mismatch errors.

The issue lies in how the type annotations are being applied or interpreted in the failing test code.
